                  <data x="2012" y="12,450"/>
                  <data x="2014" y="14,800"/>
                  <data x="2016" y="16,900"/>
                </dataset>
              </graph>
              <chapter>
                <title>China</title>
                <paragraph>The Chinese central bank strengthened yuan fixing as dollar dropped after the speech.
                  In the money market in that day, the Chinese central bank injected $9.2 billion through seven-day reverse-repurchase agreement to maintain liquidity in the market.
                  Over the past few months, the Chinese economy has been facing liquidity issue, prompting PBOC to conduct money market operation on daily basis.</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>PBOC injected 60 billion yuan in the market.</paragraph>
                </chapter>
                <chapter>
                  <title>Australia</title>
                  <paragraph>Australian stocks tracked a surge in the U.S. and bonds in the region climbed after the speech
                    reasserted the central bank’s gradual approach to raising interest rates. Shares in Sydney
                    snapped a three day decline after U.S. equities erased their losses for the year, with Yellen indicating
                    deteriorating world growth warranted a slow approach to tightening monetary policy.</paragraph>
                    <paragraph>Australian Dollar has rised 12% since mid-January.</paragraph>
                  </chapter>
                  <chapter>
                    <title>South Korea</title>
                    <paragraph>The South Korean won notched a 2016 high on Wednesday morning after U.S. Federal Reserve Chair Janet Yellen speech.
                      The won is likely to continue extending its gains in the near-term and find its footing at around the 1,140.0 level.
                      The risk-off sentiment could still crop up given a shaky global oil price and a strengthening Japanese yen.</paragraph>
                      <paragraph>The most important stock market is Samsung Electronics Co Ltd that were down about 0.50% after Fed governor speech.</paragraph>
                    </chapter>
                    <chapter>
                      <title>Japan</title>
                      <paragraph>The yen, which typically moves at odds with Japanese shares, was steady at 112.74 per dollar following a 0.7 percent bounce Tuesday that snapped its seven-day decline. The Japanese currency is headed for a 0.1 percent drop in March, after
                        surging in February. The yen now has to contend with negative rates not having the desired effect,
                        the Bank of Japan assessing other unconventional monetary policy options and a U.S. central bank unlikely to raise rates.</paragraph>
                      </chapter>
